the american football conference (afc) championship game (also unofficially referred to as the afc title game) is one of the two semi-final playoff games of the national football league (nfl), the largest professional american football league in the united states. the game is played on the penultimate sunday in january and determines the champion of the american football conference (afc). the winner then advances to face the winner of the national football conference (nfc) championship game in the super bowl. the game was established as part of the 1970 merger between the nfl and the american football league (afl), with the merged league realigning into two conferences. since 1984, each winner of the afc championship game has also received the lamar hunt trophy, named after the founder of the afl and longtime leader of the kansas city chiefs.